Here is a function that checks if any number in an array of 5 numbers is a prime number and prints it if so:

```js
function checkPrime(arr) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    let num = arr[i];
    let isPrime = true;

    if (num <= 1) {
      continue; 
    }

    for (let j = 2; j < num; j++) {
      if (num % j == 0) {
        isPrime = false;
        break;
      }
    }

    if (isPrime) {
      console.log(num);
    }
  }
}
```

To use it:

```js
let numbers = [2, 5, 8, 11, 15];
checkPrime(numbers); // Prints 2 and 11
```

This loops through each number in the array, checks if it is prime by seeing if it is divisible by any other numbers between 2 and itself. If it makes it through without being divisible it is prime, so we print it.

There are a few ways in TypeScript to tell the type system that a value will have a more specific type than its declared type allows:

1. Use a type assertion:

```ts
let x: string | number;

// I know x will be a string 
let y = (x as string).toUpperCase();
```

2. Use control flow narrowing:

```ts 
let x: string | number;

if (typeof x === 'string') {
  // Within this block TypeScript knows x is a string
  x.toUpperCase(); 
} else {
  // Here TypeScript knows x is a number
}
```

3. Use a user-defined type guard:

```ts
function isString(x: string | number): x is string {
  return typeof x === 'string';
}

let x: string | number;

if (isString(x)) {
  // Now TypeScript knows x is a string
}
```

4. Use a discriminated union:

```ts
interface StringValue {
  kind: 'string';
  value: string;
}

interface NumberValue {
  kind: 'number'; 
  value: number;
}

let x: StringValue | NumberValue;

if (x.kind === 'string') {
  // TypeScript knows x is a StringValue
}
```

So in summary, TypeScript gives you tools to tell the type system when you know a value will have a more specific type than its declared type. This helps catch errors and acts like an assertion.

